* horizontally, formula_10
* vertically, formula_11
* diagonally, formula_12

=== Derivation of the angle-of-view formula ===

Consider a rectilinear lens in a camera used to photograph an object at a distance formula_13, and forming an image that just barely fits in the dimension, formula_2, of the frame (the film or image sensor). Treat the lens as if it were a pinhole at distance formula_15 from the image plane (technically, the center of perspective of a rectilinear lens is at the center of its entrance pupil where chief rays meet):

Now formula_16 is the angle between the optical axis of the lens and the ray joining its optical center to the edge of the film. Here formula_17 is defined to be the angle-of-view, since it is the angle enclosing the largest object whose image can fit on the film. We want to find the relationship between:
* the angle formula_17
* the &quot;opposite&quot; side of the right triangle, formula_19 (half the film-format dimension)
* the &quot;adjacent&quot; side, formula_15 (distance from the lens to the image plane)
Using basic trigonometry, we find:formula_21which we can solve for &quot;α&quot;, giving:

formula_22

To project a sharp image of distant objects, formula_15 needs to be equal to the focal length, formula_24, which is attained by setting the lens for infinity focus. Then the angle of view is given by:

formula_25

Note that the angle of view varies slightly when the focus is not at infinity (See breathing (lens)), given by formula_26 as a rearrangement of the lens equation.

==== Macro photography ====

For macro photography, we cannot neglect the difference between formula_15 and formula_24. From the lens formula,

formula_29

The absolute transverse magnification (the absolute ratio of the image height to the object height) can be expressed formula_7, we can substitute formula_13 and with some algebra find:

formula_32

Defining formula_33 as the &quot;effective focal length&quot;, we get the formula presented above:

formula_1 where formula_35.

A second effect which comes into play in macro photography is lens asymmetry (an asymmetric lens is a lens where the aperture appears to have different dimensions when viewed from the front and from the back). The lens asymmetry causes an offset between the nodal plane and pupil positions. The effect can be quantified using the ratio (&quot;P&quot;) between apparent exit pupil diameter and entrance pupil diameter. The full formula for angle of view now becomes:

